126582b7-2d16-443d-b9e7-004b7ccbab47.0fef7e1d-e64f-4b23-b6b7-648f2c00d975.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);
126582b7-2d16-443d-b9e7-004b7ccbab47.273f79df-8c0d-4c70-9bd1-311fa79f8545.description=
This operation iterates through a list of values. It is not recommended to modify the value of the "list" and "separator" inputs during the iteration process.

Inputs\:
    list - The list to iterate through.
    separator - A delimiter separating the list elements. This may be single character, multi-characters or special characters. 
Default value\: ‘,’ (comma).
Examples\: In case the list is\:
"One \n simple %
list to test the operation."
1. If the separator is "\n" then the elements returned per iteration by this operation are\:
   1st iteration\: One
   2nd iteration\: simple %
   3rd iteration\: list to test the operation.
2. If the separator is "%" then the elements returned per iteration by this operation are\:
   1st iteration\: One \n simple
   2nd iteration\: list to test the operation.
3. If the separator is "test" then the elements returned per iteration by this operation are\:
   1st iteration\: One \n simple %
                      list to 
   2nd iteration\: the operation.

Results\:
    resultString - The current list element (if the response is "has more").

Responses\:
    has more - Another value was found in the list and it has been returned.
    no more - The iterator has gone through the entire list. This response is returned once per list iteration.  A subsequent call to the List iterator operation restarts the list iteration process.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
   The position of the iterator in the list is tracked by each step's unique identifier. Therefore, you can simultaneously iterate through the same list from multiple steps.

126582b7-2d16-443d-b9e7-004b7ccbab47.594c5762-7d86-4df9-ab57-98e4a6f63ed9.description=
This operation runs a command, allowing you to specify whether it runs locally (no port to be specified), via SSH, Global Shell, ROSH, Telnet, or RSH.

Inputs\:
    host - The host name or IP address.
    port - The port number used to connect to the host.
    username - The user name used to connect.
    password - The password associated with the "username" input. If using a private key file, this is the passphrase for the file.
    protocol - The protocol used to run the command. 
Valid values\: SSH, ROSH, GlobalShell, Telnet, RSH, REXEC, local, WMI, NASConnectTelnet, HPOM
    timeout - The time to wait for the command to complete (in milliseconds). Increase this value if you are getting incomplete output results or a timeout.
Default value\: 90000 (90 seconds), 600000 (if protocol->WMI)
    returnImmediately - Only for local protocol. If "true", the operation executes the command and returns a result immediately.  It does not wait for the command to finish.
Valid values\: true, false.
Default value\: false.
    runAsSudo - Specifies whether to run the command as SUDO user (used by SSH)
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    command - The command to run.
    arguments - The arguments to pass to the command.
    environment - Specifies the environment variables and values that need to be defined when running the command.
    startDir - The path to the starting directory.
    pty - Specifies whether to use pty (used by SSH, GlobalShell)
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    privateKeyFile - The absolute path to the private key file on the RAS host (used by SSH, GlobalShell).
    sasHost - The host on which to run the ROSH command.
    sasHostUsername - The user name used to run the ROSH command on "sasHost".
    usernamePrompt - The prompt message for the user name. Used by the Telnet protocol. 
Default value\: When used by the NASConnectTelnet protocol, the default value is "NAS Login\:".
    passwordPrompt - The prompt message for the password associated with the "usernamePrompt"  input. Used by the Telnet protocol.  
Default value\: When used by the 'NASConnectTelnet' protocol, the default value is "Password\:"
    outputPath - The network accessible path where to store the temporary files. If you do not specify this input, it points to '\\host\admin$\temp\'. If this path is not accessible, change it to use another share to which the host local system account has write access. By default, the path needs to be changed on Windows 2000 systems.
    nasDevice - The NAS device on which to run the command when using the 'NASConnect' protocol.
    nasDeviceConsoleMode - The NAS device console mode used to run the command scripts running the command on the specified NAS device. If you leave this input empty, command scripts are not used, and the connections to the NAS device and the command are issued directly in the console. This is not recommended. Due to error handling capabilities limitation, the result might be a success even if the command failed to run. You can find the values for this input in the NAS web interface, as a drop-down list when creating a new command script (for example, Cisco IOS enable).
    hpomNode - The node on which to run the command.
    hpomProtocol - The protocol used to communicate with HPOM 
Valid values\: HTTP or HTTPS.
    characterSet - The name of the character set used for stream encoding and decoding between the RAS and target machine.
Valid values\: SJIS,EUC-JP, UTF-8
Default value\: UTF-8 (used by SSH, GlobalShell, Telnet, RSH, REXEC)
    escapeCharacters - A list of characters, sepparated by comma, that will be escaped from the command's arguments list. By default, this input is left blank and no characters are escaped.

Hidden Inputs\:
    useDelegation - This input only applies to the WMI protocol. If set to "true" the operation will use the 'Delegate' impersonation level and the 'Kerberos' authentication protocol. If 'false', empty or missing the operation will use 'Impersonate' for the impersonation level and the default authentication protocol (which is NTLM).
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. Used to determine the operation response, specifying whether the operation is successful or not.
    stdOut - The standard output (STDOUT) of the command.
    stdErr - The standard error (STDERR) of the command.
    exitStatus - Every command returns an exit status (sometimes referred to as a return status or exit code). A successful command returns a 0, while an unsuccessful one returns a non-zero value that usually can be interpreted as an error code. The supported protocols are\: SSH, ROSH, GlobalShell, local, WMI. 
Examples\: 0 for a successful command, 126 if the command cannot execute.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully or if the command was not yet terminated.

Notes\:
1. Telnet protocol - Since telnet is a shell protocol, not a remote execution protocol, the response is always  successful if the command is ran in the remote shell.  The return code of the specified command cannot be determined in this protocol.  If you must use the telnet protocol with this operation, make sure to check the command results. Consider using the SSH or REXEC protocol instead.
2. The "exitStatus" result for Telnet, RSH, REXEC, NasConnectTelnet, HPOM will be "" (empty). For Windows host, it will be run the following final command\: "cmd /V\:on /c   ^& echo \!ERRORLEVEL\!". For Linux host, the "; echo $?" will be appended to "command" input or "arguments" input (if the last one is not empty). 
3. If RSH protocol is used the command should be run from a machine that is in the same network as the one from the host input.
4. WMI protocol can be used only from Windows RAS. If you want to make connection from a non Windows RAS use other protocols like SSH, Telnet.
5. To enable Delayed Variable Expansion in local command, use "SETLOCAL EnableDelayedExpansion".
126582b7-2d16-443d-b9e7-004b7ccbab47.752408b7-3676-4485-b41b-ce1fbf753861.description=
 
This operation reads the content of a file. The operation can be used to read the entire file content in one step or to iterate the file line by line.

Inputs\:
    source - The full path and filename of the file to be read. A UNC path can be supported as the source file path.
    filter -  Regular expression filter to be applied to each line (leave blank for no filter). If this filter is not blank, all rows that contain the filter string will be returned. If no match is found, no lines will be returned.
    store - Whether to store results in the session for retrieval. If "store" is set to true, then all matching lines are pushed into the Session and then subsequent calls to the operation results in the next line being returned.  If set to "false", the file will be iterated and in any iteration the number of remaining lines that matched the "filter" will be returned.
Valid values \: true, false
    delimiter - If specified, the entire content of the file  will be read, the specified value will be used as a delimiter between the rows and  the resulting content will be returned. If left blank, the next row will be returned for each subsequent call. 
    user - Username to use for thread impersonation on the RAS host when reading.
    password - Password for the user.
    eofReset -  If set to true, after the No More response has been returned once, the operation will restart reading the file from the beginning on the next call.
Valid values\: true, false
    characterSet - The character set of the file to read from. For invalid or empty input value the default encoding will be used. 
Valid values\: UTF-8, UTF-16 and UTF-32 
Default value\: UTF-8

Responses\:
    more lines - More lines are available to be read in the session.
    no more lines - No lines are available for reading in the session.
    failure - If something went wrong. 

Results\:
    returnCode - This is the primary output. It is 0 if the operation completed successfully  (or if more rows are available when iterate is set to true), 1 if no more items (if iterate is set to true) and -1 in case of failure. 
    COUNT- The number of lines that matched the filter, or if no filter specified, the total lines read (if iterate is false, or delimiter is not null). Otherwise, it returns the number of lines remaining in the session. This result is only returned in line-by-line mode.
    returnResult - Each row by turn (if iterate is true and delimiter is blank) or all rows separated by the delimiter (if iterate is true and delimiter is not blank).
    exception - An exception message if the operation fails.

Note\:
1. If you are using UTF-8 special characters(for example japanese characters), please ensure that your file is encoded in UTF-8 and not in ANSI wich is the default file encoding in windows when you are creating a new file.
2. The "filter" and "eofReset" fields are taken into consideration only if iterate is set to true. Otherwise, they have no impact on the result.
3. If i"store" is set to "true" and "delimiter" is not null, the entire file may or may not still be fully read at once, depending on size. 
4. If "store" is set to "true", then all matching lines are pushed into the Session and then, subsequent calls to the operation, result in the next line being returned.

Examples\:
    The following examples are used to illustrate the behavior of the operation for three specific use cases. For these examples, the operation will use as the input source a file called "example.txt", with the absolute path "C\:\Program Files\example.txt" and the following content\:
        "line1
         line2
         line3
         line4"
1. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "store" input field is set to "true" and the "delimiter" input field is not left blank\:
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        store\: true
        delimiter\: ,
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will have the following value\: line1,line2,line3,line4
2. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "store" input field is set to "true" and the "delimiter" input field is left blank\:
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        store\: true
        delimiter\:
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the file will be iterated row by row in four subsequent calls. At each call, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will contain the value of one line from the file, in the same order as they are found in the source file (i.e. line1, line2, lin3, line4). 
3. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "store" input field is set to "false" and the "delimiter" input field is left blank\:       
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        iterate\: false
        delimiter\:
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, all matching lines will be iterated and the "returnResult" field will contain, at each iteration, the number of lines remaining to be iterated (i.e\: 4, 3, 2, 1).
